[normal]10. What is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the [bold]UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]A large part of the UK domestic mining and quarrying industry is owned and operated by relatively few large multinational companies, the majority of which are foreign-owned. A high percentage of total outp
[normal]ut of construction aggregates in the UK 
[normal]is
[normal] from quarries operated by 
[normal]four companies
[normal]. These companies are all vertically integrated and include 
[normal]cement manufacturing 
[normal]in the UK or Europe. The indigenous silica sand and ball clay/ kaolin industries are also do
[normal]minated by just two large, foreign owned companies. Ownership of the coal industry across the UK is more diverse. 
[normal]The
[normal] consolidation of mining and quarrying companies
[normal] is partly
[normal] 
[normal]in
[normal] response to competition for land use. The commercial risk involved in 
[normal]setting
[normal] aside time and financial resources 
[normal]needed to obtain a licence to operate 
[normal](planning permission and environmental permits) 
[normal]in the UK is relatively high by both world and European standards. The response of the market to this risk has been for companies to r
[normal]eplenish reserves by acquisition (in order to access additional permitted sites or to deny them to rivals) and by vertical integration (for cement companies to secure supplies of vital aggregate raw materials). The result is a relatively small group of lar
[normal]ge companies who have sufficient investment capability to meet permitting costs and maintain a portfolio of different supply options. 
[normal]This situation may present
[normal] 
[normal]a barrier
[normal] to entry for smaller local operators
[normal]. It may also encourage 
[normal]consolidation of producti
[normal]on at fewer, larger quarries where 
[normal]larger
[normal] companies can take advantage of economies of scale
[normal], as well as
[normal] the ‘trading’ of sites with permitted reserves between companies
[normal] and the
[normal] giving up of dormant sites in scenic areas such as National Parks in exchange 
[normal]for a licence to operate elsewhere.
